stylometry: Managers will consider the amount of time a customer waits in line, the average amount of time it takes a customer to be served, the amount of customers that come in, the amount of servers available and the given time.  The objective is to determine how many lines there should be, if there should be one long line and each customer goes to the next available several server or if there should be several small lines with one server.  The costs would be hiring more servers or equipment (cash registers, computers, etc.) to increase efficiency.  The best way to determine without spending money first is to run a queuing model.
